'''William Henry ("Bill") Kruskal''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|r|ʌ|s|k|əl}}; October 10, 1919 – April 21, 2005) was an [[United States|American]] [[mathematician]] and [[statistician]].  He is best known for having formulated the [[Kruskal–Wallis one-way analysis of variance]] (together with [[W. Allen Wallis]]), a widely used [[non-parametric statistics|nonparametric statistical method]].

==Biography==
Kruskal was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref>[http://americanjewisharchives.org/publications/journal/PDF/1972_24_01_00_brown.pdf American Jewish Archives: "Two Baltic Families Who Came to America The Jacobsons and the Kruskals, 1870-1970" by RICHARD D. BROWN] January 24, 1972</ref> in [[New York City]] to a successful fur wholesaler.<ref name=StAndrews>[http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Biographies/Kruskal_William.html University of St Andrews, Scotland - School of Mathematics and Statistics: "William Kruskal" by J.J. O'Connor and E.F. Robertson] November 2006</ref>  His mother, [[Lillian Rose Vorhaus Kruskal Oppenheimer]], became a noted promoter of [[Origami]] during the early era of television.  He was the oldest of five children, three of whom, including himself, became researchers in mathematics and physics; see [[Joseph Kruskal]] and [[Martin Kruskal]].  Kruskal left [[Antioch College]] to attend [[Harvard University]], receiving bachelor's and master's degrees in mathematics in 1940 and 1941.  He pursued a Ph. D. in [[Mathematical Sciences]] at [[Columbia University]], graduating in 1955. During the [[World War II|Second World War]], Kruskal served at the [[Naval Surface Warfare Center Dahlgren Division|U.S. Naval Proving Ground]] in [[Dahlgren, Virginia]].  After brief stints working for his father and lecturing at Columbia, he joined the [[University of Chicago]] faculty as an instructor in statistics in 1950.  He edited the [[Annals of Mathematical Statistics]] from 1958 to 1961, served as president of the [[Institute of Mathematical Statistics]] in 1971, and of the [[American Statistical Association]] in 1982.  Kruskal retired as Professor Emeritus in 1990. He died in [[Chicago]].

